            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Marin County to a pragmatic architect father and a classically trained Indian dancer mother, River Surya Jones\u2019s life has been a study in balancing structure and flow. Her very name was a compromise: \"River\" from her mother, Anjali, who saw life as a spiritual current, and \"Jones\" from her father, Richard, who grounded the family in suburban reality. Her middle name, Surya, was a nod to the heritage she felt but didn't always understand as a child.\n\nDrawn to form and expression, River pursued a Bachelor of Fine Arts at Mills College, focusing on sculpture. She moved to San Francisco in the mid-90s, immersing herself in the pre-dot-com bohemia of the Mission District. However, the art world proved disillusioning, and a gnawing anxiety began to shadow her creative spirit. This led to her first turning point: a yoga class taken on a whim in her late twenties. On the mat, she found a connection between the physical discipline of sculpture and the spiritual grace of her mother's worldview. It felt like coming home.\n\nRiver dedicated herself to the practice, eventually completing teacher training. For a decade, she taught at studios across the city, honing her craft. The defining moment came when her mother passed away after a battle with cancer. The loss shattered River but also clarified her purpose. Using a small inheritance, she took the biggest risk of her life and opened her own studio, \u201cSoma Flow,\u201d in Hayes Valley.\n\nToday, at 53, River lives a life of intentional simplicity. Her small apartment is just a half-mile walk from her studio, a journey she makes daily with her rescue greyhound, Bodhi. Her income is modest for San Francisco, but her wealth is in the community she\u2019s built\u2014a diverse group of students who find solace in her classes. She is deeply connected to Hayes Valley, cherishing its blend of old-world charm and modern energy. Her aspiration isn\u2019t to expand her business, but to deepen its impact. She dreams of launching a mentorship program for new teachers of color, ensuring the practice that saved her remains an accessible sanctuary for all in a city that is constantly changing."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being six, sitting on the thick shag carpet of their Marin home. Her father was at his drafting table, the pencil-sharpener smell of cedar in the air, while her mother\u2019s silver ankle bells chimed softly from the kitchen. Richard called her \u201cRiver,\u201d and Anjali called her \u201cSurya.\u201d It wasn\u2019t confusing; it was a fact. In that moment, she understood she was the bridge between a straight line and a flowing current. This early realization of her dual nature became the central quest of her life: finding balance.\n\n2.\nIt was 1998, in a stuffy Mission studio. She was 28, coiled tight with anxiety and disillusionment from the art world. Lying in Savasana, she expected nothing. But then, a dam inside her broke. Tears streamed silently down her temples, pooling on the worn wooden floor. It wasn\u2019t sadness; it was a profound, soul-shaking relief. For the first time, her body and spirit felt like a single, integrated whole. The experience wasn\u2019t just a class; it was the first anointing of her true calling.\n\n3.\nAfter her mother died, the inheritance check felt like a lead weight in her hand. She was 43, standing in a dusty, vacant storefront in Hayes Valley. The air smelled of old wood and new possibility. As she signed the lease, her hand shaking slightly, she felt Anjali\u2019s presence so strongly it was almost a whisper. The grief was a raw ache, but signing her name transformed it into fierce purpose. She wasn\u2019t just starting a business; she was building her mother a living, breathing memorial.\n\n4.\nThe greyhound was all angles and stillness, curled in the corner of his kennel. When the shelter volunteer brought him out, he didn\u2019t bound forward but simply walked over and leaned his long, elegant head against her leg. She saw the story of a life lived for someone else\u2019s purpose in his deep, soulful eyes. In that instant, rescuing him felt like rescuing a quiet part of herself. That afternoon, Bodhi\u2019s gentle presence became the silent, grounding rhythm of her daily life, just after she turned 45.\n\n5.\nLast Tuesday, as evening light streamed into Soma Flow, she watched her students in final rest. A young Latina woman, a tech worker, a retired teacher\u2014all breathing in unison. Her gaze fell on a new student, a young Black artist whose face held a familiar mix of exhaustion and hope. A wave of profound gratitude washed over her. It wasn't pride, but a quiet fulfillment. The idea of the mentorship crystallized in that moment, no longer a dream but a necessary promise to keep the door open."
